{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601706/1938021301/0056.xml":{"full_text":"Peaks Since September Set\nBefore Sales Cause Par\ntial Reactions.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 12.\u2014Trade views\nen progress of the conference report\non the farm bill through the House\nand Senate accounted for fluctuations\nof more than $1.50 a bale in cotton\nduring the past week.\nSharp rallies carried new crop posi\ntions above 9 cents and to the best\nlevels since September beiore enough\nrealizing and Southern selling ap\npeared to cause partial reactions. May\ncontracts, which have advanced from\n8.54 to 8.89, closed yesterday at 8.81\nagainst 8.58 a week ago.\nRapid House action in adopting the\nconference report inspired general\nbuying on expectations the provisions\nof the bill would apply to the 1938\ncrop in holding acreage down to pro\nduction of about 10,700.000 bales.\nEven more trade attention was given\nto the Smith amendment to the re\nport, designed to hasten the payment\nof 2 cents per pound of the bounty\ndue growers on their 1937 production\nwhen compliance with the 1938 ad\nministration program is proven.\nActive March liquidation prior to\nfirst notice day on February 23 con\ntinued and open interest in the near\nmonth was reduced by about 185,000\nbales during the week, leaving 320,\n000 bales still outstanding in that de\nlivery. Quiet conditions prevailed in\ncotton goods markets and mill buying\nof spot cotton was restricted. Janu\nary domestic consumption w-as esti\nmated at 435.000 bales by the New\nYork Cotton Exchange Service against\n678,000 in January a year ago.\nNew Orleans Cotton.\nNEW ORLEANS. Feb. 13 UPi.\u2014After\nreacting from an Initial advance, cotton\nrallied again later today and last prices\nwere steady. 5 to 8 points net higher.\nProspects for prompt passage of the\nfarm bill were the main influences behind\nthe better feeling.\nThe range of futures follows:\nOpen. High. Low Close.\nMarch _8.90 S.94 8 88 8 94\nMay -8.90 9.01 8.93 9 01\nJuly -9.03 9.08 9.00 9.08\nOctober _ 9.10 9 13 9 io i:i\nDecember_9 11 9 14 9.11 9.14\nJanuary .9.13 9.10 9.13 9. lei\nSpot cotton closed steady. 9 points up.\nSales. 3 318: low middling. 7.09: middling.\n909: good middling. 9.04: receipts. 3.753;\nstock, 834.835.\nINDUSTRIAL RATE\nGAINS MODERATELY\nAssociated Press Index Turns Up\nlor Second Time Since Drop\nStarted Last Summer.\n8r the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 12.\u2014Industrial\nactivity turned up this week for the\nsecond time since the recession started\nlast summer.\nThe gain, however, was moderate.\nThe Associated Press seasonally ad\njusted index rose to 70.4 per cent of\nthe 1929-30 average from 70.2 last\nweek and compared with 99.5 a year\nago.\nSteel mill operations, cotton manu\nfacturing and total freight carloadings\nwere the principal gainers. Automo\nbile production and electric power out\nput, after adjustment for seasonal va\nriations, slumped to new lows for the\npast two years or more.\nThe index, with its seasonally ad\njusted components based on the latest\navailable statistics and with 1929-30\nas 100, compared as follows:\nLatest Previous Year\nweek. week. ago.\nComposite index_ 70.4 70 2 on 5\nAutomobile prod __ H0.2t 60.5 87 1\nSteel mill activity 41.2 40 n 108 2\nCotton mfg. activity 82.8 18 4 127.2\nElectric power prod 108.2* lOR.n lirt.6\nResidential building 4.YS 45.R 71.5\nTotal carloadings 61.6 50.4. 73.7\ntNew 1038 low.\n\nNew Peak Is Set\nBy W estern Aut^\nSupply Profits\nBy the Associated Press.\nKANSAS CITY, Feb. 12. \u2014West\nern Auto Supply announced today net\nearnings for 1937 reached an all-time\nhigh of $2,475,177, equal to $3.29 a\nshare, compared with $2,066,015, or\n$2.73 a share, on a comparable num\nber of shares a year ago.\nTotal sales for the year, the com\npany announced, were $36,911,995, an\nIncrease of 43.5 per cent over 1936.\nSpeare\n(Continued From Page E-l.)\nof a high percentage of any new rate\ngranted on coal.\nCarloadings for the week of January\n8 were a little in excess of the week\nprevious. They are still 17 per cent\nless than a year ago. with the l06s\nchiefly in the industrial centers. Roads\nwest of the Mississippi report a fair\nvolume of tonnage originating in their\nterritory, but scant contributions from\nEastern lines.\nDepends on Industry.\nRecovery in railroad traffic in the\nterritory where it is at lowest ebb will\nA. P. Market Averages\n\n4 STOCKS ->kL/\\ Ml +~H7S\nj5--S5\nv~\n100-*-*V-100\nBONDS\n95-f--_ZYV-95\n90-W***-A-90\n--85\n80-L-80\n75-\u2014-75\nCOMMODITIES A\n90----V VY--90\n70- --\u2014--70\n100-industrial_^n(^v:::\":1I0\nACTIVITY s>r 1U0\n90\u2014Ay^-V\u2014\u201490\n80\u2014-f\\jL-\\f-1-80\n70 ^\\\u00bbrj-^-70\n80---(j-60\ni i i i i i i ii i i T1TH Ill'll I I I I I I II I I\n__ FEBRUARY\n1935 1936 1937 1938\nA majority of the economic barometers of the Nation\u2019s\nhealth turned up this week, as is indicated by the above chart\nof Associated Press averages. Commodities alone declined\nduring the period. Bonds were the biggest gainers, ivith the\nrail issues that had recently been under pressure setting the\npace. Stocks improved modestly on the thinnest volume in\nyears. The industrial picture, measured by activity in the\nmajor industries, brightened somewhat.\nCommodity Price\nChanges for Week\nBy A. A. PATTON,\nAssociated Press Stalistici\u00bbn.\nNEW YORK. Fob. 12.\u2014Commodity\nprices slid deeper into new low ground\nthis week, slumping to the lowest level\nin more than three years.\nAgricultural staples alone, under i\nthe leadership of cotton, were able\nto breast the receding tide. Moderate\ndeclines in wheat and corn were more\nthan offset by gains in oats, rye and\ncotton.\nEvery other important commodity\ngroup chalked up a new low for the\nyear.\nThe Associated Press weighted index\nof 35 important wholesale staples\ndropped to 71.12 per cent of the 1926\naverage from 71.73 last week and\ncompared with 90.05 a year ago.\nLivestock Irregular.\nLivestock quotations were mixed;\ncattle dipped sharply as prospective\nsupplies loomed larger, while lambs\ni were marked up fractionally. Hogs\nj were unchanged.\nAfter a modest upturn the week be\nfore, non-ferrous metals reacted as\nzinc and lead producers slashed prices\nin an effort to scare up new business.\nLead quotations were cut twice, when\nthe first reduction failed to bring in\nany orders. Antimony was pushed\nup slightly.\nTextiles continued to recede. Al\nthough cotton cloth held at its recent\nlevel wool gave ground as inventories\nmounted and sales dried up. Silk\nnudged ahead a fraction.\nOther Groups Uneven.\nOther industrial raw materials were\n.uneven; recessions in turpentine and\nlinseed oil outweighing upturns ;n\nrubber and bituminous coal.\nCommodities destined for the house\nwife's market basket were cheaper.\nSugar, cocoa and butter dipped, while\neggs and coffee moved up.\nThe index, with its components\nbased on 1926 as 100, compared as\nfollows;\nPiev. Year\nFeb 11. week. ago.\n3n commodities *71.15 71.73 90.05\nIndustrial *85.47 85.55 9] 51\nFood __ *59.75 HI 05 75 11\nLivestock _ *71.35 73.8] 93.54\nAgriculture _ 75.89 72.H5 103.09\nTextile *53.58 53 H5 79 51\nNon-ferrous metal *09.55 70.45 87.74\n*1938 low\nBlaw-Knox Co.\u2014Lewis Foundry\nMachine Division of company re\nceived a contract for two balanced\nthree-high rolling mills equipped with\nautomatic screw down from Bengal\nSteel Co., Ltd., of India.\ndepend on how far the automobile, the\niron and steel and the building con\nstruction industries expand this spring.\nIt is important, therefore, to consider\nthe effect on them of the new price\nscale just established by the steel\nmakers. This ought to encourage the\nautomobile manufacturers, as they\nbenefit most from the $4-a-ton reduc\ntion in steel sheets.\nWhether or not competitive con\nditions in the iron and steel trade in\nvolve price schedules from which the\nrailroads and the steel structural in\nteiests would prosper remains to be\nseen.\nThis week's reports indicated a slight\nrecession in steel production and a\ndecline in the price of scrap after a\nWASHINGTON STOCK EXCHANGE\nYEAR 1938\n(Reported by W. B. Hlbbs k Co.. Hibbs Building. Washington. D. C.)\nTRANSACTIONS ON THE WASHINGTON STOCK EXCHANGE UP TO AND INCLUDING\nFRIDAY, FEBRUARY 11. 1938.\nBONDS. Approx.\nSale*. PUBLIC UTILITIES. Open. High. Low. Close, yield.\n$1,000 Ana. k Pot. Rlv. R. R. 1st 6% 1949__ 60 60 60 60 11.60%\n16.600 Capital Traction 1st 6% 1947- 66 70 66 70 10.40\n8,000 City Sub. Ry. 1st 5% 1948_ 65 66 66 65 13.20\n8,600 Washington Gas Light 5% 1960- 116 116 116% 116 3.90\n8.000 Washington Oas Light 5% 1958_106% 106% 108% 106% 4.65\n3.000 Washington Ry. El. 4% 1961_ 107 107 107 107 3.35\nMISCELLANEOUS.\n1.000 Chevy Chase Club 4%% 1957..104% 104% 104% 104% 3.90\nSTOCKS.\nPar Div.\nPUBLIC UTILITIES. Value. Rate.\n8 Pot. El. pow. 8% pid_$100 $6.00 113V* 113% 113 113 6.30\n58 Pot. El. Pow. 5%% \u00a3fd_ 100 6.50 111% 113 111% 113 4.92\n230 Wash. Oas Light pld_ No 4.60 97 99 97 98% 4.65\n41 Wash. Gas Light com_ No 1.20 23 23 23 23 6.21\n58 Wash. Ry. El. pfd_ 100 6.00 109 110% 109 110% 4.54\n169 Capital Transit _$100 9% 9% 8 9 _\nBANKS AND TRUST COMPANIES.\n17 Riggs com 100 eS.OO 295 295 290 290 2.70\n180 Amer. 80c. k Trust-100 e8.00 246 250 243 243 3.20\nMISCELLANEOUS.\n85 Carpel Corp. _ No 2.00 21 21 21 21 9.62\n25 Lanston Monotype_ 100 *4.00 68% 68% 68% 68% 6.67\n844 Mergenthaler Linotype- No 2.00 24V* 24% 23 23% 8.60\n81 Peoples Drug pfd 100 6.50 112 112 111% 111% 6.80\n820 Real Estate Mtge. k Guar, pfd 10 4% 4% 4% 4%\nt Security Storage- 26 6.00 107 107 107 107 4.ST\n2% extra. *Plua extras. **30e paid June, 1987.\nPRICES GO DOWN\nON METAL MARKET\nLead and Zinc Quotations Cut\nDuring Week\u2014Slash in Domes\ntic Copper Also Talked.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. Feb. 12\u2014The metals\ntrade experienced a busy week, high\nlighted by the amicable settlement of\nthe wage conference in steel and the\neasier tone in the nonferrous group.\nLead and zinc were reduced and\n12 cent a pound, respectively, and\nthere were rumors the domestic cop\nper price might be further reduced\nunless there was a decided pickup\nin demand.\nExport copper held relatively steady\nfor a time, reflecting armament buy\ning and purchases against currency\ndepreciation, but later the foreign\nmarket eased also. The latter was\ncoupled with the reaction at London,\nthe German situation and the new\ncabinet crisis in Rumania. The do\nmestic copper price was held at 10\ncents by both producers and smellers.\nLead experienced two successive re\nductions of U cent a pound, the sec\nond after the first failed to stimulate\nbuying interest,\nZinc declined U cent, reflecting the\nrapidly increasing stocks and poor\ninquiry.\nTin prices fluctuated irregularly\nover narrow limits, and finished the\nweek net unchanged.\nWOOL DEMAND REMAINS\nMODERATE AT BOSTON\nBy the Associated Press.\nBOSTON, Feb, 12 (United States\nDepartment of Agriculture) .\u2014A slight\nincrease in demand for wool on the\nBoston market last week showed some\nfurther expansion this week, but\nactivity on the whole continued very\nmoderate.\nMills restricted buying operations in\nthis market to covering immediate\nneeds.\nOccasional lots of wool that became\navailable in the West at prices below\nBoston quotations found outlets to\nusers who were anticipating near\nfuture needs. Forward buying, how\never. was very conservative.\nCombing bright fleece wools in Bos\nton were quoted at 28 to 29 cents in\nthe grease for fine delaine, at 29 to 30\ncents for half-blood, at 28 to 30 cents\nfor three-eitfhths-blood and at 27 to\n29 cents for quarter-blood.\nsteady rise in it since the first of\nthe year.\nSpeaking before the Senate Unem\nployment Committee on January 22,\nBenjamin Fairless, president of the\nUnited States Steel Corp., said that\nsteel prices could not be reduced with\nout a like cut in the costs of pro\nduction, which involve wages. Less\nthan three weeks later his company\nextended the March, 1937, agreement\non wages and hours with the Steel\nWorkers' Organizing Committee. Si\nmultaneously Independent steel man\nufacturers made a sharp slash in the\nquotation of one of their important\nproducts.\nThe new wage contract permits of a\nreadjustment on 10 days\u2019 notice after\nFebruary 28. So it is fair to assume\nthat, if a price war, meanwhile, de\nvelops between the United States Steel\nCorp. and the Independents the\neconomic philosophy of Mr. Fairless\nwill have another test; also that of\nPresident Roosevelt, who has recently\nsaid that price reductions should not\ncome out of wages. In the present\ncapitalistic system they do, and prob\nably will again, however unfortunate\nand unsocial this may be.\nInflation Talked.\nOpinion is becoming more general\nthat the probable way out of the de\npression will be by the avenue of credit\nInflation, by means of Government\nspending. Demand for this is grow\ning.\nIt is expressed in a broader relief\nprogram, involving an extra appropria\ntion by Congress of $250,000,000 to\ncarry through the remainder of this\nfiscal year.\nIt is to be expected that the \"infla\ntionists\u201d in Congress will resume their\nefforts to restore the price level and\nassist in raising the \"purchasing power\nof the dollar.\u201d\nThere is a persistent belief abroad\nthat President Roosevelt will exercise\nhis privilege and once more \"devalue.\u201d\nThis may be the basis on which larger\ncommitments have been made recently\nby foreign speculators in American\nshares, plus what appears to be a more\nfavorable outlook for political condi\ntions in Europe and in the Far East.\n(Cc prrisht, 1*38. to ths Herts Aaurlaea\nHiwswe Alliance, be.)\nAUSTRALIAN SALES\nLOWER MEAT\nLarge Exports to Europe\nCaused by Closing of\nOriental Markets.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, Feb. 12.\u2014Big exports of\nwheat from Australia to Europe are\nJust now dazing traders the world\nover, and incidentally are holding\nUnited States wheat down.\nFor at least the time being, Australia\nis harvesting dollars wholesale as a\nconsequence, and American wheat ex\nporters who had expected to HU the\nbulk of Europe\u2019s breadstulfs needs at\nth's time find themselves mainly as\ntonished lookers-on, correspondingly\nout of pocket. The chief suggested\nreason is that China and Japan are\nso busy fighting each other that any\nadequate outlet for Australian wheat\nin the Orient has not only been made\nimpracticable, but has made Aus\ntralia\u2019s wheat prices the cheapest in\nthe world.\nHard Varieties Required.\nFaced by such a difficulty, Chicago\nwheat specialists are emphasizing\nstatements that if importing nations\nare to maintain the quality of their\nflour, substantial quantities of hard\nw'heat will be required for mixing with\nAustralian soft varieties, and that\nUnited States better quality strong\nwheats should sooner or later meet\nwith increased demand.\nCompared to one week back, Chi\ncago wheat prices yesterday were >/4\nof a cent lower; corn, 14-\u2022% up;\noats, unchanged to \u2019i advance; rye,\nshowing from T1* decline to 1\\ bulge,\nand provisions varying from 22 cents\nsetback to 7 cents jump.\nAdding to troubles of American ex\nporters of wheat is the fact that the\nAustralian official crop estimate has\nbeen Increased to 170.000.000 bushels.\nThis is about 10.000.000 bushels larger\nthan preliminary returns and 20.000,\n000 bushels more than last year. Be\nsides, forecasts now are that India w'ill\nhave the largest wheat crop achieved\nin several years.\nFalls Where Least Needed.\nOn the other hand, moisture of late\nfor domestic Winter wheat has been\nalmost entirely confined to areas where\nleast needed. However, the growth pe\nriod of the crop taken as a whole does\nnot begin for about a month. A ma\njority of traders consequently are in\nclined to belief that although dust\nstorms may be reported from time to\ntime, it is still too early for definite\nforecasts except that the Southwest\nwill start with a great shortage in sea\nsonal precipitation, and will make gen\nerous rains imperative if another cur\ntailed crop is to be averted.\nCorn values are being lifted a little\nby lightness of receipts and by un\nfavorable weather. Oats tend to fol\nlow corn. Rye has not responded well\nto moderate export buying.\nPro\\ isions partly show advances\nparalleling hog market gains.\nNEW YORK BANK STOCKS\nCLIMB 2.45 PER CENT\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK. Ppb. 12\u2014 New York j\ni City bank stocks moved higher during\nthe last week and registered fair gains\nat the close, according to records com\npiled by Hoit, Rose Troster.\nThe aggregate value of 16 leading\nissues on February 11 totaled $1,387.\n771.000, compared with $1,354,639,000\nat the close of the previous week, an\nincrease of *33,132,000, or 2 45 per\ncent.\nThe current average yield of the 16\nissues of 4.75 per cent, compares with\na yield of 4.87 per cent on February 4.\nThe current market value is now 99\nper cent of the known book value,\ncompared with 97 per cent a week\nago.\nBased upon current figures the 16\nissues are now quoted at an average\nof 14.5 times their known earnings,\nagainst 14.2 times on February 4.\nCHICAGO LIVE STOCK.\nCHICAGO. Feb. 17 1.4*1 (United States\nDepartment of Agriculture!.\u2014Hogs. \u2022\u2019.mill,\nincluding 7.000 direct: market slow steadv\nto 1(1 lower than Friday average: scattered\nlots good and choice. 190-3]5 pounds.\n,.80-8.50; strictly choice lightweignts ab\nsent but quotable tin to 8.15 or better:\nshippers took 700: holdover, l otto Com\npared week ago: Weights 770 pounds\ndown, steady to 5 lower: 77(1 pounds up.\no 15 oil. parking sows 5-15 higher.\nCattle. 300: calves. 100. compared Fri\nday last week medium weight and heavy\nsteers 75 higher: yearlings strong, week\nend undertone dull general market clos\ning under weeks best time: largely fat\nateer run again: early improvement due to\nabridged receipts: most fat steers. 0.85\n8.50. little above n.nn: best light year\nlings. 0 00: prime heavies. 11.50: no cri\nterion general market as choice outstand\ning cattle sold at 0 00-10,50; beef trade a\nlittle broader: heifers steady to 75 higher;\nweighty kinds 110 most: common and me\ndium light heifers continue active: choice\nheavy heifers, 9.00: best lights, 8.00; beef\ncows. 75-40 higher: cutters and bulls\nstrong to 75 up: vealers 75-50 higher.\nSheep, 3.000. none direct: for week end\ning Friday. 1.500 direct; compered Friday\nlast week fat lambs 15-75 higher: year\nlings strong: sheep 75-40 up; feeding\nlambs about steadv: week's fat lamb top.\n7,75, paid at close for few loads choice\naround 81-90 pound iambs: week's bulk\n7.75-7 65 closing bulk 7.50-7.65. with\nstrictly choice 95-98 Dound lambs at out\nside; clipped lambs. 6.35-6.65 bulk 6.60:\ntop yearlings 7.00. bulk 6.50-7.00: top\nslaughter ewes 4.40. bulk 3.50-4.00: me\ndium and good feeding lambs 6.00-6 65,\nmostly.\nFOR TRADE RISE\n\nNeeded Readjustments Seen\nAhead as U. S. Steel\nReaches Agreement.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 12.\u2014The first\ncut in steel prices, and the agreement\non wages between the United States\nSteel Corp. and its workers, fore\nshadow a series of needed readjust\nments which may start industry mov\ning again, and \u201cclear the way for a\ngeneral upturn in buying of raw' ma\nterials and manufactured goods,\u201d says\nBusiness Week today.\n\"This does not mean that actual\noperations in February will show\nmuch or any improvement, or that\nthe month will be other than dis\nappointing. But it gives ground for\ngreater confidence in the March out\nlook.\u201d\nFive Points Listed.\nIn its weekly \"business outlook,\u201d\nBusiness Week economists set down\nthe following points to reach the con\nclusion that readjustment, not re\nduction, will take place:\n1. There 1s no {Jossibility of a dras\ntic liquidation of wage rates; this\ncould easily bring about social dis\nturbance, and is not to be expected in\nany case.\n2. In spite of political speeches, or\ndeclarations by labor leaders anxious\nto prove their zeal or entrench them\nselves for bargaining purposes., a\nmoderate reduction in wage rates is\nboth unavoidable and wholesome.\n3. Where labor costs per unit of\noutput cannot be cut through the\nwage-reduction channel, they will be\ncut through Increased labor effort (to\nprotect jobs that are less secure) and\nthrough installation of labor-saving\ndevices.\n4. Wages are not the only key to re\ncovery; business needs volume more\nthan it needs lower operating costs,\nand readjustments outside the field\nof labor will ultimately produce the\nvolume, regardless of wage levels.\n5. Regardless of intermediate shocks\nand let-downs, the reduction of labor\ncosts and other needed readjustments\nwill go forward steadily, pointing to\nward a spring pick-up in business and\na more solid recovery later in the year.\nEfficiency Held Key.\n\u201cThe secret of recovery must lie in I\nthe improvement of efficiency,\u201d says\nBusiness Week. \u201cThis involves greater\neffort by the individual worker, im\nprovements in methods and labor\nsaving machinery. Capital goods in\ndustries have a significant role to\nplay; machinery salesmen are bat\ntling the depression on the front of\nlabor costs.\u201d\n\"Any one who looks at the matter\nthoughtfully must realize that it is\npassible for wage rates to be either\ntoo high or too low for the welfare\nboth of labor and the community.\nIn times when wages, interest rates,\nwholesale and retail prices and other\nelements in the price structure are\nin balance, individuals are able to\nexchange their commodities or serv\nices, to their mutual benefit. The re\nsult is full employment and activity.\nIn the President's words, \u2018industry\nin its own interests should ask for its\nproducts what the people can afford\nto pay,\u2019 and the same rule necessarily\napplies to labor, the farmers and all\neconomic groups.\u201d\nTORONTO STOCKS.\nTORONTO. Feb. 1*1 ..*>)\u2014a group of\nmfru-!!nlor us s,eP\u00bbed mto the stock\nmark*, spotlight today, moving in vol\nume ai higher prices while other groups\nmoved sluggishly The holiday on the\nNew York market had a curtailing effect\non the trade in the industrials and the\nin ter listed leaders remained around Fri\ndays closing prices. In the penny golds\nthere was a turnover of 300.000 shares\nm the first hour.\nOmega. Augite. Maralgo and Bankfield\ngamed 3 to Jo cents. Hard Rock stood\nout among the medium price issue* ad\ncents on a trade of more than\n5omoo Shares CacLeod Cockshutt held\nonly part of its early gain\nChaneeR in the senior golds were lim\nited to small fracuoriR, The close was\nno for Pickle Crov. O Brier.. Little Long\nLac. Kerr Addison. Lench. Kirkland Hud\nson and Uchi\nConsolidated Smelters registered a point\ndecline and International Nickel and\nNorancia were steady.*\nLake Sulphite registered further weak\nness while other paper issues were un\nchanged.\nMONTREAL STOCKS.\nMONTREAL Felj. 1 i-Fi \u2014-Stock Price*\nturned slightly downward at the close of\nthe short session todav. Losses, however,\nwere narrow on a dull market.\nSuch papers as Bathurst and Price\nBros sold off small fractions Consolidated\nSmelters held unchanged and International\nNickel gamed a fraction. Small losses\nappeared in the general list for Canadian\nIndustrial Alcohol. Gypsum Imperial Oil.\nInternational Pete and Massey Harris.\nRails were fairly firm except for a loss\nof >2 for Canadian Car. Shawiniean eased\na fraction, but Montreal Power and Gat\nineau firmed.\nCanadian Bronze came out with a point\ngam Dominion Steel showed a fractional\nadvance.\nCHICAGO POTATOES.\nCHICAGO F>b 12 i/P> iUnited States\nDepartment of Agriculture).\u2014Potatoes. 91;\non track. 100: total United States ship\nments. NO*.\u2019: for Idaho Russet Burbanks,\nmarket dull and weaker undertone, other\nstock steady; sunplies moderate; demand\nvery slow: sacked, per hundredweight.\nIdaho Russet Burbanks. U. S No. 1. 1.30\n35: Colorado Red McClures. U. S. No. 1.\n1.40-50: North Dakota Bliss Triumphs.\n85 per cent U. S. No. 1 and better. 1.05\n10: Wisconsin Round Whites. U. S No. 1.\n1.05-07**; new stock steady, supplies mod\nerate. demand light: track sales less\nthan carlcts. per bushel crates. Florida\nBliss Triumphs. U. S. No. 1. 1.45-54.\nHow Is Business?\nShowing Currant Business Activity Compared With the Same Week a Year Ago.\n____ MAS. AAA MAY JUNE JulyI AU8 SEPT OCT NOV DEC JAN PEPAUART\n^1937 1938\n-Present\nBusiness\n\u2014--\u201412.3#\nCT .1 i I Below\n\u2014-\u2014=tfPfi\n-w\nI I 11 1 I 11 I I 1 1 1_\nC1NKRAL BUSINESS ACTIVITY for thn country Indicated by Bank*Deblte outside\nT. City. Shaded areas show week of activity above the corresponding week of tho\nprevious year. Black areas indicate declines from tame weeks twelve months earlier#\nACTIVITY BY FEDERAL RESERVE DISTRICTS\nCheek Transactions compared with the same week a year ago\nTsltsa\" haw Vark fhil.d.laliia I Clavalaad I KIsCbmI J Atlanta I\n-3S.I>?t.l,_-34.1% \u201413.0% -IQ.8% 9.8%\u2014 -S.3*\nChiaOda St. L\u00abii I Mia.AAp.lla I Kauai City I Dallat S.PraaaUaa\n-is.r% I +f.l% 1 \u201418.4% I -9.5% 1 -S.3B \u2014XO.7% I\nLEADING BAROMETERS\nShowing Trand of Important Factor* Chant*\nPresent Trand From Year Ado\nBusiness In Dollars (Checks Cashed) Upward\nEmployment (Dept, of Labor). Downward \u2014'97\nWages (Dept, of Labor). Downward IS O\nCMt of Living (Ind. Conf. Board)... Downward 12*9\nWholesale Prices (Fisher\u2019s Index)... Downward 86\nAgricultural Prices (Bureau of Labor) Downward 22%\nMovement of Good. (Car Loadings). Downward _ i.'2\nRetail Trade (Fed. Res. Board). Downwwd 2 1\nBuilding Contracts (F. W. Dodge).. Upward 4. go\nFailures (Dun\u2019s).. Downward T.5\u20192\nBond Prices (Dow-Jones). Upward 14\u2019n\nStock Prices (Composite Dow-Jones) Upward 30*4\nStock Mkt. Vol. (Shares Traded) Onward mli\nAO righto mmttd, Cmmhrldgt Ametolm, Bottom\nCurb Market Transactions\nFor Week Ending February li, 1938:\nIssues Ad- De- Un- New \u201938New \u201938\nShares Traded Traded vances dines changed Highs Lows\nMonday _ 86,000 287 95 102 90 2 23\nTuesday _113,000 322 155 72 95 5 28\nWednesday ..127,000 298 142 74 82 10 19\nThursday ...113,000 299 125 72 102 9 13\nFriday. 94,000 257 73 83 101 8 16\nBaltimore Markets\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nBALTIMORE, Md., Feb. 12.\u2014Few\nchanges took place during the week In\nlive poultry prices. The week started\noff with rather light receipts but ship\nments improved later and the supply\nwas ample to meet all demands.\nThere was good inquiry during a\npart of the time for capons and tur\nkeys.\nPrices however, remained steady.\nAbout the only change from last week's\nquotations was recorded by Muscovy\nducks, which are 1 cent lower. All\nother poultry prices are practically the\nsame as last week. In young chickens,\nboth large Rocks and mixed colors, are\nselling 22a24, with broilers bringing\n18a22; In fowl, Rocks are selling 21a\n22; mixed colors, 20a21; Leghorns,\n16a20, and roosters, 12al5; capons,\nweighing 7 pounds and up, continue\nat 32a33, with smaller birds selling 27a\n30. Young Pekin ducks are still\nquoted 22a23 with Muscovys bringing\n20a22. Guineas are unchanged at 60\neach for birds weighing 2 Vi pounds\nand up, and 40a50 for smaller stock.\nYoung hen turkeys are selling 34a35\nand toms, 27a28, with culls bringing\nas low as 18.\nEgg Market Weak.\nAlthough the local egg market con\ntinued weak during the period the de\nclines were only fractional. There\nwas some improvement toward the\nclose of the week and the final quota\ntions are about on the same level as a\nweek ago, with large whites bringing\na slightly higher price. Nearby cur\nrent receipts and medium sized whites\nare selling 19 dozen and large whites\nare bringing 21a22. Receipts were\nfairly large throughout the week.\nThere is little native and nearby\ngarden truck on the market. Mary\nland round white potatoes are a little\nlower, with No. is selling 1.00 per 100\npounds and a few bringing slightly\nhigher prices, while ungraded stock\nis quoted 75a90. Nearby sweet pota\ntoes are unchanged at 75a85 bushel for\nNo. is and 50a65 for ungraded. Nearby\npurple-top turnips continue at 20a\n30 half bushel, but yellows are higher\nat 75a85 per 100 pounds.\nLive Stock Market.\nCattle. 50; calves, no receipts. Com\npared with Friday last week, steers.\n25-50 higher; medium and good 900\n1.000 pounds, 7.00-8.00; 1,058 pounds\n8 20; bulls mostly 25 higher, odd-lot\nI, 093-pound heifers, 8.25; plain and\nmedium. 5.00-7.00; good beef cow-s\nscarce; few 5.50-6.00; plain and me\ndium fat cows. 4.75a5 25; low cutters\napd cutters, 3 75-4.50. Compared with\nlast week, good vealers steady, mostly\nII. 50-12.00.\nHogs. 275. Nominally steady; com\npared with last Saturday, weights from\n140 pounds up, mostly 5 lower; slaugh\nter pigs off 10; packing sows steady to\n10 lower. Good and choice 140-200\npounds quotable 9.30-55: 120-140\npounds, 8.90-9.40; 210-240 pounds,\n8.75-9.25; 250-300 pounds. 8 15-7s'\nGood packing sows, 7.00-50; stags\n6.25 down.\nSheep, 250. Compared with Friday\nlast week, steady; good and choice\newe and wether lambs, 8.50-85; weights\naveraging under 90 pounds, plain and\nmedium, 6.50-7.50; fat slaughter ewes\n4.75 down.\n\nD. C. SECURITIES.\nYesterday s closing bid and asked\nquotations on Washington Securities\nwhich are traded over the counter fol\nlow:\nBar A Ross deb 4?\u00b0^,.-,\nrwu^n*^ *nc due 1^51 JfMI\nl g c Mill 1st Us 1 94 ti -5\nHamil Real Cor 1st Ss 1945 o-\nMayf Hot Cor 1st 5s 1950\nNat Press Bla 1st :t-5s 1950\nRacquet Club 1st 5s 1945 Mr\nRiverside Apts 1st Ts 19.14 90 loo>,\nWash Audit 1st Os 1944 *5S g -1\nWash Prop Inc 7s 1952 J-J iJj\nSTOCKS.\nAnacoslia Bank j *,i\nAnacostla Finance 